Preface: "The book will, therefore, draw a limit to thinking, or rather—not to thinking, but to the expression of thoughts; for, in order to draw a limit to thinking we should have to be able to think both sides of this limit (we should therefore have to be able to think what cannot be thought). The limit can, therefore, only be drawn in language and what lies on the other side of the limit will be simply nonsense." German: Grenze: Limit, border, boundry, frontier. Wittgenstein here is stating the purpose of the text, to determine the limits of thought and language, and how they relate to reality.

"The Cosmos is all that is, or ever was, or ever will be." -Carl Sagan, Cosmos
Socrates was fat and Plato was thin (Mounce). Or maybe Socrates was thin and Plato was fat. Or maybe neither was fat, or both were fat. I don't know, but this is the logical space which can represent the fatness of Socrates and Plato. The world is whichever of these cases is true.
1.1: Socrates can be fat or thin, but the world is not the logical capacity of Socrates to be fat or thin, the world is whichever of these cases is true, along with everything else that is true.
1.1.1: So the world is a set of truths, not a set of things. Things exist in a logical space which determine the possible truths, but the world is only one of those cases.
1.1.2: If you were able to know everything that is the case, you would also know everything that is not the case. The set of true facts is the complement of the set of facts that are not true.
1.1.3: The world is not comprised of planets and stars, nor desks and chairs, because these are language concepts we've created to identify these things which are actually collections of smaller things. But the world is not comprised of atoms and quantum energies because again these are labels to discuss things inthe world. The world is a set of facts that are true, not a set of concepts or labels or things.
1.2: Wittgenstein had trouble with examples of facts this atomic (Mounce p.20). This point became a source of later criticism. Any facts we can represent in language are large amounts of compounded simpler facts, by the nature of language.
1.2.1: Changing a fact about the world might have many complicated consequences; a bridge might collapse if it were not suspended correctly, but the type of true facts that represent the world are not logically dependent on each other. Any one singular fact could be different and the others could remain the same.

"Bertrand Russell: The Logic and Philosophy of Language" (Edited by Nicod and others) — contains references to this manuscript. Published in: "The Philosophy of Logical Atomism" (1918) and also in later collections. The 1984 publication: The manuscript was published under the title "The Theory of Judgment" in "The Collected Papers of Bertrand Russell, Volume 17: The Philosophy of Logical Atomism", or in some scholarly editions like: "The Collected Papers of Bertrand Russell, Volume 17" (1984) — which contains the previously suppressed manuscript.
